Government officials were recently caught <a href="http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-11-04/chinese-officials-implicated-in-body-snatching-scheme/5864114" target="_blank">buying corpses from grave robbers</a> to hit their targets. The government's campaign was originally supposed to free up cemetery land for farming and development.

&nbsp;

&nbsp;

Anticipating weak third-quarter economic data, prime minister Shinzo Abe will postpone the tax increase <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/11/us-japan-politics-election-idUSKCN0IV28D20141111" target="_blank">and call for December elections</a>, Reuters reported, citing local media. The last sales tax hike, from 5% to 8%, contributed to the economy's <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2014/08/13/japans-gdp-falls-by-6-8-in-the-second-quarter-on-sales-tax-rise/" target="_blank">sharp contraction</a> in the second quarter. Preliminary third-quarter GDP figures are due Monday.

